Imagine a very long website with many sections (so an HTML specification on one page). If the user requests a specific section (e.g. page.html#section7), how would it be if the web server streams this section first and then the other sections?
Stream order:
1. The beginning of the HTML document until <body>
2. HTML for Section 7
3. HTML for Section 1, 2, 3 etc.
Then the browser would ensure that sections 1 to 6 are displayed *above* section 7 on the website.
Does that make sense? Would that be helpful?
The linked section (#section7) should be rendered as quickly as possible without having to implement elements again with JavaScript. I simply want to have an extra-long HTML document, but the linked sections should be rendered as quickly as possible. This should work with HTML.
The content could be streamed, and then the browser would insert all <contents> into the <div>.
<div id=sec1> </div>
<div id=sec2>  </div>
usw.
<div id=sec7> section 7… </div>
<contents for=sec1> section 1… </contents>
<contents for=sec2> section 2… </contents>
etc.
It would not be streamed in sequence, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it had been streamed in sequence.
@user22 You can also rearrange documents without JS. You should not use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string parameters so that the server knows which section you want to load first. When rearranging the parts, you have several options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use a template with sections
@user23 Yes. The problem is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not match the DOM order. It would be useful to have an HTML function that allows non-sequential streaming, but the browser then arranges the content in the DOM order.
But the idea with the slots looks promising. I'll try that.
@user22 Oh, do you want the browser to put the DOM order in order?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first, so the user can see it as quickly as possible. If that could be done without influencing the DOM order, that would be good, then the browser would ensure that the resulting DOM order corresponds to the visual order.
So, Section 7 should be streamed first, but the final result should look as if all sections were streamed in sequence.
@user22 @user23 Check out PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
